docs.abstract: Not being able to watch a football game is a problem. But not having a strategy is a bigger problem.
docs.snippet: Not being able to watch a football game is a problem. But not having a strategy is a bigger problem.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the United States government last shut down over a congressional impasse, in 2013, I was 20 days shy of my discharge from the Marine Corps, in Camp Pendleton, Calif. A last-minute bill, signed the day before the rest of the federal government’s appropriations were set to expire, guaranteed that I and the rest of the military would continue to receive our paychecks. It was comforting, I suppose, to know that at least Congress could muster the bipartisan will to accomplish something, but even at the time it struck me as absurd: The same Congress and administration that jumped at the opportunity to demonstrate how much they cared about the troops seemed perfectly comfortable with the status quo of endless war. Missing a paycheck would have been an inconvenience. Fighting in a war that I still don’t understand, however, has affected me and my brothers and sisters in uniform in far more pernicious and long-lasting ways.

headline.main: Congress Suddenly Cares About the Troops When a Shutdown Looms. What About the Rest of the Time?

docs.abstract: The cinematographer for “Mudbound” and “Black Panther” on the male-dominated profession.
docs.snippet: The cinematographer for “Mudbound” and “Black Panther” on the male-dominated profession.
docs.lead_paragraph: In January, you became the first woman nominated for an Oscar for best cinematography, for your work on “Mudbound.” Did you know that it was going to be a male-dominated profession when you first started out? I don’t know that I was entirely conscious of it, because I started in photography, which is closer to 50-50. There’s this idea that there are more female cinematographers now because cameras are lighter, which is the stupidest thing I’ve ever heard. Cinematography speaks to everything that women do inherently well: It’s multitasking, it’s empathy and it’s channeling visuals into human emotion. Little by little, I realized that I was an anomaly, but I tried not to focus on it, or to, at least, see it as a way to stand out in the crowd and bring something to the table that most people don’t.

headline.main: Rachel Morrison Wants More Women Behind the Camera

docs.abstract: Study toddlers. Find a reason to fall.
docs.snippet: Study toddlers. Find a reason to fall.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Observe toddlers — they’re the best and funniest fallers out there,” says Tim Cunningham, who has performed in more than a dozen countries with Clowns Without Borders. A pratfall is a staged tumble, often onto your buttocks, for comedic effect. In addition to new walkers, these dramatic spills have long been a go-to move for physical comedians, including Charlie Chaplin and Buster Keaton.

docs.abstract: A way to reveal just how wild your backyard can be.
docs.snippet: A way to reveal just how wild your backyard can be.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last year, I received an email from my dad, under a mildly worrisome subject line: “Mystery critter ???” There was no body text, but attached was a 10-second video clip, shot in the eerie grays of infrared night vision. It showed a furry creature, about the size of a Pomeranian, charging away from the camera and down a driveway. Midway through the video, the animal stops abruptly, turns slightly and stares back — if not directly at the camera, near enough that its retinas catch the light and, for a moment, glow. Then it slouches off, away from the camera and into the darkness. Watching it again, I noticed that the driveway looked oddly familiar — it was my childhood home.
